Access controls for AI Systems
===============================
Model Access - Who gets to interact with the AI model?
    Inference Access - Querying a model and receiving a response
    Training/Fine-tuning Access - Permits direct alteration of a model's weights
    Configuration Access - Covers the ability to modify a model's operational parameters w/o retraining

Data Access - Who can interact with information flowing in and out of an AI system?
    Training Data Access - the backbone of any model.
        - Least privelege is important!
    Inference Data Access - User permissions must be used to filter accessibility before query is processed
    Output Data Access - Who can view what the model produces?
        - Log access should be tiered based on sensitivity of data
    Vector Store and Embeddings Access
        - Vector store is numerical representation (embeddings) of knowledge base documents
            - Access to this is pretty much the same as access to underlying documents
        - Access to the vector store should mirror the privileges granted to the underlying documents

Agent Access - An agent is an entity that executes actions on behalf of a user or organization
    - What is the agent allowed to access?
    Agent Identity and Delegation - Identity of an agent is not as simple as an identity of a human
    - Safest approach is to have the same permissions as the user it represents, but is restrictive
        - More flexibility means more risk
    Scope Limitations - boundaries for permissible agent behavior
        - Action scoping - confines agent to explicit set of operations
        - Resource scoping - dictates which systems, datasets, and APIs the agent may interact with
        - Conditional scoping - allows agent to do certain things when certain conditions are met